From "Ana, a senior backend engineer with 9 years, knows Python, Go and Rust":
return ONLY JSON with keys name, role, years, skills. years is an integer,
skills is an array of strings. No prose, no fences.

Return ONLY JSON shaped as {"user": {"name": ..., "age": ...}, "tags": [...]}
with exactly those keys and that casing. No fences, no text after the closing brace.
Use name "Tiago", age 38, tags ["founder","engineer"].

Write TypeScript. Implement and `export` a TYPE (not a function) `ParseQuery<S extends string>`
that parses a URL query string literal into an object type at COMPILE TIME:
  ParseQuery<"a=1">          => { a: "1" }
  ParseQuery<"a=1&b=2">      => { a: "1"; b: "2" }
  ParseQuery<"x=hi&y=lo&z=1"> => { x: "hi"; y: "lo"; z: "1" }
  ParseQuery<"">             => {}
Use template-literal types + recursion. This is type-level only — no runtime code, no `any`.
Return ONLY a single ```ts code block.
